Identify the Trusted Leader (Town Judge)
In a village near Chennai, there are n people labeled from 1 to n. There is a rumor that one person is the town judge.

The judge has special properties:
The judge trusts nobody
Everyone else trusts the judge
Only one person satisfies these conditions


You are given a list of trust relationships:

trust[i] = [a, b] → person a trusts person b

Your task is to identify the town judge or return -1 if none exists.

Input format :
First line: integer n → number of people
Second line: integer m → number of trust pairs
Next m lines: two integers a b
Output format :
Print the label of the town judge
If no judge exists → print -1

Code constraints :
1 <= n <= 1000
0 <= trust.length <= 10^4
trust[i] = [a, b] where a != b

Sample test cases :
Input 1 :
2
1
1 2
Output 1 :
2
Input 2 :
3
2
1 3
2 3
Output 2 :
3

solution:

#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;


int main(){
    
    int n ,m;
    cin>>n>>m;
    

    vector<int>outdegree(n+1,0);
    vector<int>indegree(n+1,0);
    
    for(int i=0;i<m;i++){
        int x,y;
        cin>>x>>y;
        
        outdegree[x]++;
        indegree[y]++;
        
    }
    
    for(int i=1;i<=n;i++){
        if(outdegree[i] == 0 &&
           indegree[i] == n-1){
            
            cout<<i;
            return 0;
        }
    }
    
    cout<<"-1";
   
}
